value.title: 1 in 5 Americans have confidence Biden can unite the country: poll
value.excerpt: Just one in five Americans have “a great deal of confidence” in President Biden’s ability to make good on his goal to unify the country, according to a new poll released Sunday.

value.title: Biden may pick up the tab for San Francisco homeless hotels
value.excerpt: San Francisco hotels used to house homeless people may be fully funded by the federal government this year, thanks to an executive order signed by President Joe Biden signed last Thursday.

value.title: Trump offers first remarks since leaving office: 'We'll do something'
value.excerpt: Former President Donald Trump was mysterious about his future plans in his first public remarks since leaving the White House earlier this week, but he suggested action is in the works, according to a report.

value.title: ABC’s 'This Week' edits out Schumer’s unfortunate Trump gaffe on Senate floor
value.excerpt: Democratic Senate leader Chuck Schumer was ridiculed on Friday for an unfortunate gaffe he made while criticizing former President Donald Trump’s supposed influence on the Jan. 6 Capitol riot. But Schumer’s error was conveniently edited out in a clip that aired Sunday on ABC’s “This Week.

value.title: Trump impeachment trial is 'stupid,' 'bad for the country': Rubio
value.excerpt: The Senate impeachment trial of former President Donald Trump is "stupid" and "bad for the country," Sen. Marco Rubio said.

value.title: Kamala Harris' Roe v. Wade post draws Tennessee governor’s response: ‘Abortion isn’t healthcare’
value.excerpt: Tennessee Gov. Bill Lee spoke out last week after Vice President Kamala Harris issued a statement to mark the 48th anniversary of the Supreme Court decision that legalized abortion nationwide.

value.title: Biden, UK's Boris Johnson discuss Paris accord, trade, coronavirus
value.excerpt: President Biden had his first phone call with British Prime Minister Boris Johnson on Saturday, where Johnson pressed the new president for a U.S.-U.K. trade deal.

value.title: Trump impeachment manager Swalwell on trial: 'If the Senate allows witnesses, we will be ready with witnesses'
value.excerpt: Rep. Eric Swalwell, who will help prosecute former President Trump for "incitement of insurrection," said House impeachment managers are prepared to call witnesses at the upcoming Senate trial.

value.title: LIVE UPDATES: Trump impeachment trial delayed until February
value.excerpt: Follow for the latest updates on Trump's impeachment.

value.title: Rep. Ilhan Omar calls on Biden to back 'recurring cash payments' until economy recovers
value.excerpt: Omar and other progressives have argued that Biden’s proposal does not go far enough to address the current financial crisis.

value.title: Biden says 'nothing we can do' to change pandemic 'trajectory' in coming months
value.excerpt: Biden addressed his administration’s response efforts during a press briefing on two executive orders meant to provide food assistance to low-income families and protect workers’ rights during the pandemic.

value.title: Ari Fleischer: 'Big government is back' under Biden
value.excerpt: President Biden's approach to tackling the economic crisis brought about by the coronavirus pandemic shows that "big government is back" in Washington, former White House Press Secretary Ari Fleischer said Friday.

value.title: Reince Priebus: 'Tough time for the Republican Party’ but Biden's actions easy to unite against
value.excerpt: Former White House Chief of Staff Reince Priebus told "America’s Newsroom" Friday that it’s a "tough time for the Republican Party" since President Biden was sworn in, but Biden's actions may make it easier for the party to unite.

value.title: Biden suggests delayed impeachment timeline may be 'better'
value.excerpt: Biden suggested having more time to get his Cabinet nominees confirmed may help jumpstart his policy agenda.

value.title: Alejandro Mayorkas: What to know about Biden's DHS pick
value.excerpt: President Biden has nominated Alejandro Mayorkas to be the next secretary of the Department of Homeland Security (DHS), who will take a key role in the closely watched area of immigration policy.

value.title: Georgia U.S. Attorney Pushed to Resign by Trump Aides Rejoins Law Firm
value.excerpt: The former top federal prosecutor in Atlanta, whom White House officials pushed to resign earlier this month because then-President Donald Trump was upset he wasn’t doing enough to investigate unproven claims of election fraud,

value.title: Joe Biden putting 'Saudi Arabia first' by halting Keystone XL pipeline: Sen. Daines
value.excerpt: Sen. Steve Daines, R-Mont., believes President Biden killing the Keystone XL pipeline shows he’s putting "Saudi Arabia first," not American workers.

value.title: Gingrich: Dems 'methodically trying to destroy conservatism' with Biden as 'pleasant cover'
value.excerpt: President Biden's "radical" inner circle is working to "destroy" the legacy of President Trump, former House Speaker Newt Gingrich warned on "Hannity" Thursday.

value.title: Biden proposes extending nuclear arms treaty with Russia for 5 years
value.excerpt: President Joe Biden has proposed extending a nuclear arms treaty with Russia before it expires next month, White House press secretary Jen Psaki said during a Thursday press conference.

value.title: Obama praises Biden's executive order blitz: 'This is a time for boldness'
value.excerpt: Former President Barack Obama praised President Biden on Thursday for enacting a sweeping slate of executive orders within hours of his inauguration as president.

value.title: New York Times contributor loses think tank job over tweet suggesting Biden should 'lynch Mike Pence'
value.excerpt: A contributing opinion writer for The New York Times was fired from his think tank job Thursday over a tweet that jokingly suggested former Vice President Mike Pence be lynched in order to unify the country.

value.title: Biden has ‘bigger issues’ to worry about than following own mask mandate: Psaki
value.excerpt: President Biden has “bigger issues” to worry about than wearing a face mask at the Lincoln Memorial as he celebrated his Inauguration, according to White House press secretary Jennifer Psaki.

value.title: McConnell: Biden ‘took several big steps in the wrong direction’ on Day One
value.excerpt: Just one day after President Biden spoke of unity in his inaugural address to the nation, Senate Minority Leader Mitch McConnell says the Democrat president has headed in "the wrong direction."

value.title: Tara Reade says watching Biden's inauguration was 'exceptionally hard': I want to 'wake up from a nightmare'
value.excerpt: Tara Reade, the former Senate staffer who came forward during the 2020 campaign  with a sexual assault allegation against Joe Biden, is speaking out about her former boss taking the oath of office as the 46th president of the United States.

value.title: House expected to approve waiver for Biden's Defense Secretary nominee Lloyd Austin
value.excerpt: President Biden's nominee for Secretary of Defense is expected to clear an important hurdle Thursday in his pathway to confirmation of the new cabinet.

value.title: Logan: Media institutions won't 'admit they were wrong about so many stories' during Trump era
value.excerpt: Affiliates of the mainstream media will not admit they were wrong about how they conducted journalism during the Trump administration, Fox Nation host Lara Logan said on Thursday.

value.title: LIVE UPDATES: Anti-Biden Antifa protesters take to the streets in Portland, Seattle overnight
value.excerpt: At least eight adults were arrested for crimes ranging from rioting and possession of a destructive device to reckless burning.

value.title: Pence touts time as VP, including Hoosier Justice Barrett, in return to Indiana: 'There's no place like home'
value.excerpt: Former Vice President Pence wished new President Biden and Vice President Harris well as he returned to Indiana on Wednesday afternoon, while also expressing gratitude for his time as vice president.

value.title: First 100 days of Biden, Obama, Clinton: Escalating spending to address economic challenge
value.excerpt: The first 100 days of a two-term presidency mark about 3% of the eight-year span, but since President Franklin Delano Roosevelt, this brief early window of opportunity has been used to judge a new commander in chief’s agenda.
